{{Infobox cemetery | name = Meiktila War Cemetery | image = | imagesize = | caption = | map_type = Burma | map_size = 100 | map_caption = Location of Meiktila War Cemetery, Burma. | established = | country = [[Burma]] | location = [[Meiktila]], [[Mandalay Division]] | coordinates = {{coord|20.883|95.883|display=inline}} | type = Turkish military of WWI | style = | owner = | size = | graves = | website = | findagrave = | political = }}
The '''Meiktila War Cemetery''' is one of the two memorial burial grounds of [[Military of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman soldiers]] in [[Burma|Burma (Myanmar)]]. It is situated in [[Meiktila]], [[Meiktila District]] of central [[Mandalay Region]]. Ottoman soldiers are buried in the cemetery, who died after they became [[prisoner of war]] in the [[Middle Eastern theatre of World War I]] and were sent by [[British Armed Forces]] to a [[labor camp]] in this country.<ref name="ntv">{{cite news |url=http://arsiv.ntvmsnbc.com/news/445511.asp |newspaper=[[NTV (Turkey)|NTV-MSNBC]] |title=Myanmar’da Türk Şehitliği’nin akıbeti meçhul |date=2008-05-08 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-09-29 }}</ref><ref name="aspb">{{cite web |url=http://sehityakinlari.aile.gov.tr/tr/5050/Myanmar-Turk-Sehitlikleri-Yapim-Projesi |publisher=Aile ve Sosyal Politikalar Bakanlığı |title=Myanmar Türk Şehitlikleri Yapım Projesi |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-09-29 }}</ref><ref name="h7">{{cite news |url=http://www.haber7.com/guncel/haber/953169-yurtdisinda-en-fazla-turk-sehitligi-nerede |newspaper=Haber7 |title=Yurtdışında en fazla Türk şehitliği nerede? |date=2012-11-17 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-09-29 }}</ref>
Around twelve thousand soldiers of the Ottoman Army fell into the hands of British Forces during the [[Sinai and Palestine Campaign|Sinai, Palestine]] and [[Mesopotamian campaign]]s in the [[World War I]]. The Ottoman prisoners of war were transferred to Burma, which was then [[British rule in Burma|under British rule]]. The POW's were forced to work in the construction of railroad, bridge and artificial lake. More than 800 soldiers died as a result of [[epidemic]]s, hard physical labor conditions and cruel treatment. It is not known how many of the Ottoman POW's in Burma were able to return home.<ref name="ntv"/><ref name="aspb"/><ref name="h7"/>
The cemetery in Meiktila is the most devastated one of the two Turkish military memorials in Myanmar. Currently, it is in state of an empty field and its exact location is unknown. The stone walls of the cemetery and some gravestones were plundered during and after the [[World War II]]. Around 180-190 gravestones are preserved so far, after [[Muslim]] residents in the area removed and carried them to a nearby [[mosque]]'s yard.<ref name="ntv"/><ref name="aspb"/>
Turkish government's initiatives for its reconstruction since 1965 accomplished finally in 2012 with granting of the required permission. The works, commissioned by the Military Cemeteries and Memorials Department ({{lang-tr|Şehitlikler ve Anıtlar Şubesi}}) of the Ministry of Family and Social Policies, began on January 29, 2013.<ref name="aspb"/>
==See also== * [[Thayetmyo War Cemetery]] * [[Turkish military memorials and cemeteries outside Turkey]]
