{{expand language|topic=|langcode=fr|otherarticle=Poilu|date=May 2014}} [[File:FrenchTrenchWWI--nsillustratedwar03londuoft.jpeg|thumb|''Poilus'' in a trench]] '''Poilu''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|p|w|ɑː|l|uː}}; {{IPA-fr|pwaly|lang}})<ref>''Dictionnaire canadien / The Canadian Dictionary'', [[McClelland & Stewart]], Toronto, Ontario, 1962.</ref> is an informal term for a French [[World War I]] [[infantry|infantryman]], meaning, literally, ''hairy one''. It is still widely used as a term of endearment for the French infantry of World War I. The word carries the sense of the infantryman's typically [[Rural|rustic]], agricultural background. [[Beard]]s and bushy [[moustache]]s were often worn. The poilu was particularly known for his love of [[pinard (wine)|pinard]], his ration of cheap wine.<ref name="NoraJordan2009">{{cite book|author1=Pierre Nora|author2=David P. Jordan|title=Rethinking France: Les Lieux de Memoire, Volume 3: Legacies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LMsrAQAAIAAJ|date=15 August 2009|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-59134-6|page=217}}</ref><ref name="Prestwich1988">{{cite book|author=Patricia E. Prestwich|title=Drink and the politics of social reform: antialcoholism in France since 1870|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3EG8AAAAIAAJ|year=1988|publisher=Society for the Promotion of Science and Scholarship|page=172}}</ref>
[[File:Alone at last2.jpg|thumb|''Journée du Poilu. 25 et 26 décembre 1915'' (trans. "The poilu's holiday, December 25 and 26, 1915"). French [[World War I]] poster by [[Adolphe Willette]] about a poilu's Christmas leave from the front.]] The image of the [[Wiktionary:dogged#Adjective|dogged]], bearded French soldier was widely used in propaganda and war memorials.<ref>[http://centenaire.org/fr/tresors-darchives/carte-postale/la-representation-du-poilu-dans-les-cartes-postales La représentation du poilu dans les cartes postales] {{fr icon}}</ref> The stereotype of the Poilu was of bravery and endurance, but not always of unquestioning obedience. At the disastrous [[Second Battle of the Aisne|Chemin des Dames]] offensive of 1917 under General [[Robert Nivelle]], they were said to have gone into [[no man's land]] making baa'ing noises—a collective bit of [[gallows humour]] signalling the idea that they were being sent as lambs to the slaughter. Outstanding for its mixture of horror and heroism, this spectacle proved a sobering one. As the news of it spread, the French high command soon found itself coping with [[1917 French Army mutinies|a widespread mutiny]]. A minor revolution was averted only with the promise of an end to the costly offensive.
The last surviving poilu from World War I was Pierre Picault. However, French authorities recognised [[Lazare Ponticelli]] as the last poilu, as he was the last veteran whose service met the strict official criteria.<ref>[http://dersdesders.free.fr/france.html "France, derniers poilus de la Guerre 14-18"] {{fr}}</ref> Lazare Ponticelli died in [[Le Kremlin-Bicêtre]] on 12 March 2008, aged 110.<ref>[http://www.nysun.com/national/last-french-world-war-i-veteran-dies-at-110/72831/ "Last French World War I Veteran Dies at 110",] (13 March 2008) ''The New York Sun'', Retrieved on 2008-03-19.</ref>
==See also== *[[Digger (soldier)|Digger]], referring to Australian and New Zealand soldiers *[[Doughboy]], referring to American soldiers *[[Mehmetçik]], referring to Ottoman soldiers *[[Tommy Atkins|Tommy]], referring to British soldiers *''[[A Very Long Engagement]]'', a French film in which ''poilus'' are featured
