The following is a timeline of the [[Quito#History|history]] of the city of [[Quito]], [[Ecuador]].
{{Dynamic list}}
{{TOC right}}

==Prior to 20th century==
{{History of ecuador}}

* 1487 - Incas in power.<ref name=routledge2003>{{cite book |title=Political Chronology of the Americas|year= 2003|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-35653-8 |chapter= Ecuador |chapterurl= https://books.google.com/books?id=XiOPAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA95 }}</ref>
* 1527 - "Inka ruler [[Huayna Capac]] dies in Quito along with an estimated 200,000 of his subjects" (approximate date).<ref name=heilbrunn08sann>{{cite web |url= http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/ht/?period=08&region=sann#/Key-Events |title= Northern Andes, 1400–1600 A.D.: Key Events |work= Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History |publisher=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] |location=New York |accessdate= September 30, 2015 }}</ref>
* 1533 - Quito "burnt by [[Rumiñawi (Inca warrior)|Ruminahui]]."{{sfn|Catholic Encyclopedia|1911}}
* 1534 - "Spanish soldiers, led by [[Sebastián de Belalcázar]], defeat the Inka in Quito. They name the town Villa de San Francisco de Quito."<ref name=heilbrunn08sann />{{sfn|Catholic Encyclopedia|1911}}
* 1535
** Art school founded.<ref name=heilbrunn08sann />
** Construction of [[Church and Convent of St. Francis|Monastery of St. Francis]] begins (approximate date).<ref name=heilbrunn08sann />
* 1541 - Quito attains Spanish colonial city status.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1545 - [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Quito|Catholic Diocese of Quito]] established.{{sfn|Catholic Encyclopedia|1911}}
* 1548 - Quito becomes part of the [[Viceroyalty of Peru]].<ref name=routledge2003 />
* 1551 - Colegio de San Juan Evangelista established (approximate date).<ref name=heilbrunn08sann />
* 1563 - Spanish colonial [[Royal Audiencia of Quito|Audiencia of Quito]] established.{{sfn|Marley|2005}}<ref name="Olson1991">{{cite book|editor= [[James Stuart Olson]] |title=Historical Dictionary of European Imperialism |year= 1991|publisher=Greenwood |isbn=978-0-313-26257-9 |chapter=Ecuador |chapterurl= https://books.google.com/books?id=uyqepNdgUWkC&pg=PA191 }}</ref>
* 1592-1593 - Economic unrest.<ref name="Olson1991" />
* 1613 - [[Church of the Society of Jesus (Quito, Ecuador)|Church of the Society of Jesus]] building opens.{{sfn|Cushner|1982}}
* 1718 - Quito becomes part of [[Viceroyalty of New Granada]].{{sfn|Catholic Encyclopedia|1911}}
* 1735 - Earthquake.{{sfn|Catholic Encyclopedia|1911}}
* 1765
** Social unrest.<ref name="Kuethe2014">{{cite book|author1=Allan J. Kuethe|author2=Kenneth J. Andrien|title=The Spanish Atlantic World in the Eighteenth Century: War and the Bourbon Reforms, 1713–1796|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2NFkAwAAQBAJ|year=2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-04357-2}}</ref>
** [[Church of the Society of Jesus (Quito, Ecuador)|Church of the Society of Jesus]] building completed.{{sfn|Cushner|1982}}
* 1797 - Earthquake.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1810 - [[Carondelet Palace]] built.
* 1822 - May 24: [[Battle of Pichincha]].<ref name="Olson1991" />
* 1829 - Quito becomes capital of Ecuador.{{sfn|Catholic Encyclopedia|1911}}
* 1859 - Earthquake.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1865 - Guayaquil-Quito railway built (approximate date).<ref name=routledge2003 />
* 1875 - August 6: Assassination of president [[Gabriel García Moreno|Garcia Moreno]].
* 1880 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Teatro Nacional Sucre|es}} opens.<ref name="CortésBarrea-Marlys2003">{{cite book|editor=Eladio Cortés and Mirta Barrea-Marlys |title=Encyclopedia of Latin American Theater |year= 2003|publisher=Greenwood |isbn=978-0-313-29041-1 }}</ref>

==20th century==

* 1906
** ''[[El Comercio (Ecuador)|El Comercio]]'' newspaper begins publication.<ref name=europa2003>{{cite book|title=Europa World Year Book |year= 2003|publisher=[[Europa Publications]] |isbn=978-1-85743-227-5 |chapter=Ecuador: Directory |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=XLvU9lroRuUC&pg=PA1473 }}</ref>
** Chamber of Commerce established.<ref name=europa2003 />[http://www.lacamaradequito.com/la-camara/]
** Population: 50,840.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1914 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Teatro Variedades (Quito)|es}} opens.
* 1930 - [[LDU Quito]] football club formed.
* 1932 - [[Estadio El Ejido]] (stadium) opens.
* 1933 - Teatro Bolivar opens.<ref name=cinema>{{cite web |url= http://cinematreasures.org/theaters/ecuador/quito?status=all |title=Movie Theaters in Quito, Ecuador |work=CinemaTreasures.org |publisher= Cinema Treasures LLC |location=Los Angeles |accessdate=December 30, 2014 }}</ref>
* 1937 - Teatro Capitol built.<ref name=cinema />
* 1938 - ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Últimas Noticias (Ecuador)|es}}'' newspaper begins publication.<ref name=europa2003 />
* 1950 - Population: 209,932.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1950_round.htm |work=Demographic Yearbook 1955 |year= |publisher=[[Statistical Office of the United Nations]] |location=New York |title=Population of capital city and cities of 100,000 or more inhabitants }}</ref>
* 1951 - [[Estadio Olímpico Atahualpa]] (stadium) opens.
* 1955 - [[Deportivo Quito]] football club formed.
* 1960 - [[Old Mariscal Sucre International Airport|Mariscal Sucre Airport]] begins operating.
* 1972 - Population: 564,900 (approximate).<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1970_round.htm |title=Demographic Yearbook 1975 |year=1976 |author=[[United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs]], Statistical Office |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital city and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants |pages=253-279 }}</ref>
* 1978 - [[Historic Center of Quito]] designated an UNESCO [[World Heritage Site]].
* 1982
** ''[[Hoy (Ecuadorian newspaper)|Hoy]]''<ref name=europa2003 /> and ''[[La Hora]]''  newspapers begin publication.
** Population: 866,472.<ref name=UN1995>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1990_round.htm |title=1995 Demographic Yearbook |year=1997 |author=United Nations Department for Economic and Social Information and Policy Analysis, Statistics Division |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants |pages=262-321 }}</ref>
* 1990
** May: Indigenous rights demonstration.<ref name=routledge2003 />
** Population: 1,100,847.<ref name=UN1995 />
* 1992
** September: Economic unrest.<ref name=routledge2003 />
** {{Interlanguage link multi|Botanical Garden of Quito|es|3=Jardín botánico de Quito}} established.
** [[Jamil Mahuad]] becomes mayor.
** [[Coliseo General Rumiñahui]] (arena) built.
* 1994 - [[Estadio Gonzalo Pozo Ripalda|Estadio Chillogallo]] (stadium) opens.
* 1995 - January: Economic protest.<ref name=routledge2003 />
* 1996 - March: Labor strike.<ref name=routledge2003 />
* 1997
** February: Anti-[[Abdalá Bucaram|Bucaram]] demonstration.<ref name=routledge2003 />
** September: Indigenous rights rally.<ref name=routledge2003 />
** [[Estadio de Liga Deportiva Universitaria|Casa Blanca]] stadium opens.
* 1999 - February 17: Assassination of politician [[Jaime Hurtado]].<ref name=routledge2003 />
* 2000
** January: Indigenous rights demonstration.<ref name=routledge2003 />
** [[Paco Moncayo]] becomes mayor.

==21st century==

* 2001 - January: Indigenous rights demonstration.<ref name=routledge2003 />
* 2006 - [[Quito TV]] begins broadcasting.
* 2008 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Teatro México|es}} opens.
* 2009 - [[Andrés Vallejo]] becomes mayor, succeeded by [[Augusto Barrera]].
* 2011 - Mashpi Rainforest Biodiversity Reserve established near city.<ref>{{citation |work=New York Times |title=Send in the Clouds |date= November 18, 2011 |url=http://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/18/send-in-the-clouds/ }}</ref>
* 2013 - New [[Mariscal Sucre International Airport]] opens.
* 2014 - [[Mauricio Rodas]] becomes mayor.
* 2015 - September: Forest fire.<ref>{{citation |work=BBC News |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-34267806 |title= Ecuador forest fires envelope Quito in smoke|date= 16 September 2015 }}</ref>
* 2016
** October: [[Habitat III|United Nations Conference on Housing and Sustainable Urban Development]] held in Quito.
** Population: 1,778,434.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic-social/products/dyb/index.cshtml |work=Demographic Yearbook 2016 |year=2017 |publisher=[[United Nations Statistics Division]] |title= Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 or more inhabitants }}</ref>

